WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.970
Another thing about me is that I have worked in the journalism

00:00:05.030 --> 00:00:08.860
tech industry for the better part of a decade before moving on

00:00:08.860 --> 00:00:12.400
to working on open social protocols, and part of my journey

00:00:12.400 --> 00:00:16.500
there was actually seeing the things that reporters and news organizations were

00:00:16.580 --> 00:00:19.710
going through and realizing that some of the change that I wanted

00:00:19.710 --> 00:00:23.360
to affect could not be done solely by working with journalism institutions

00:00:23.360 --> 00:00:23.560
.

00:00:23.560 --> 00:00:27.440
And so I ended up moving upstream into working in tech companies

00:00:27.440 --> 00:00:32.120
and social media because that sort of fundamental substrate ended up being

00:00:32.190 --> 00:00:38.100
so important for the foundation for where the publishing industry and journalists

00:00:38.450 --> 00:00:39.320
have gone.

00:00:39.320 --> 00:00:41.780
And in that span of time have linked up and met with

00:00:41.780 --> 00:00:45.520
some fascinating folks who are thinking about what this next era of

00:00:45.590 --> 00:00:50.900
journalism creation looks like and how people are connecting with communities.

00:00:50.900 --> 00:00:55.210
So I'm very happy to have with us today Justin Bank

00:00:55.210 --> 00:00:56.960
and Lauren Sack.

00:00:56.960 --> 00:00:59.390
Justin is the co-founder of Journalism Atlas and if

00:00:59.390 --> 00:01:02.460
you saw his talk earlier this morning it was awesome.

00:01:02.460 --> 00:01:04.460
Also iterates very quickly.

00:01:04.460 --> 00:01:07.140
It was great to see a slide of Aaron who had given

00:01:07.250 --> 00:01:10.700
a talk immediately beforehand in there too.

00:01:10.700 --> 00:01:11.700
We can just do things.

00:01:11.700 --> 00:01:13.260
It's great.

00:01:13.260 --> 00:01:16.090
And Journalism Atlas is a wayfinder for the future of

00:01:16.090 --> 00:01:20.800
news media designed to connect audiences with independent creators who are telling

00:01:20.800 --> 00:01:24.150
the stories they choose with purpose for the communities they cultivate and

00:01:24.150 --> 00:01:24.460
serve.

00:01:24.460 --> 00:01:26.990
Which sounds very well aligned with the things that we talk about

00:01:26.990 --> 00:01:29.880
here at this conference and in this community.

