Thank you all for having me.

00:03:31.720 --> 00:03:32.620
Delighted to be here.

00:03:32.620 --> 00:03:33.680
And thank you for the introduction.

00:03:33.680 --> 00:03:37.440
We've been at it at Local News International since August when

00:03:37.550 --> 00:03:41.690
we took buyouts from the Washington Post after creating quite a

00:03:41.690 --> 00:03:45.780
large audience on TikTok and YouTube around a creator named Dave J

00:03:45.780 --> 00:03:46.460
orgensen.

00:03:46.460 --> 00:03:49.500
If you're familiar with him, he's the more familiar

00:03:49.570 --> 00:03:51.600
face of Local News International than I am.

00:03:51.600 --> 00:03:56.410
My career has been spent at traditional organizations, PBS and The

00:03:56.410 --> 00:04:00.290
Post and the Smithsonian before that, begging them to think about

00:04:00.350 --> 00:04:05.700
new audiences and developing content for them around audiences that probably aren

00:04:05.700 --> 00:04:07.800
't interacting with them in any other way.

00:04:07.800 --> 00:04:12.480
And we decided to go independent just because of a frustration and

00:04:12.480 --> 00:04:16.850
a sadness that these organizations are not ready to support these new

00:04:16.850 --> 00:04:17.880
endeavors.

00:04:17.880 --> 00:04:19.880
Yeah.

00:04:19.880 --> 00:04:22.420
And I think that that's an amazing segue because what I

00:04:22.420 --> 00:04:26.100
really am interested in hearing about is really the mindset of journalism

00:04:26.100 --> 00:04:29.930
creators who are thinking about this particular moment in an era where

00:04:29.930 --> 00:04:34.050
, you know, publishing has certainly changed with the internet and

00:04:34.110 --> 00:04:38.380
successive generations of technology and where audiences are, that has really

00:04:38.380 --> 00:04:43.030
shifted the landscape of what publishing is and also how that serves

00:04:43.070 --> 00:04:48.910
journalism creators and people who are doing out both reporting news but

00:04:48.910 --> 00:04:50.340
also bringing it to audiences.

00:04:50.340 --> 00:04:52.920
And that business dynamic, I think, is one of the

00:04:52.920 --> 00:04:54.760
most rapidly changing things.

00:04:54.760 --> 00:04:57.880
And as people are talking about products, new products could be

00:04:57.880 --> 00:05:03.420
built, ways that creators and audiences connect, thinking about that

00:05:03.530 --> 00:05:08.380
reality of where these businesses are now and the needs and incentives

00:05:08.380 --> 00:05:10.880
that they've got as we think about other types of futures

00:05:10.880 --> 00:05:12.240
, I think is really critical.

00:05:12.240 --> 00:05:15.080
And so I'm super curious, actually, about the story

00:05:15.080 --> 00:05:16.970
of how y'all launch and the way that you're

00:05:16.970 --> 00:05:19.230
thinking about both the content that you create and the way that

00:05:19.330 --> 00:05:21.320
you want to connect with the audiences that you're serving.

00:05:22.880 --> 00:05:26.400
Yeah, we launched knowing that we would have to put together

00:05:26.750 --> 00:05:29.680
sort of a multifaceted business and that has proven true

00:05:29.930 --> 00:05:31.920
even though we're still quite new at this.

00:05:31.920 --> 00:05:35.950
But the opportunity really comes from the way that The Post wasn

00:05:35.950 --> 00:05:38.450
't able to support us in this way and that we can

00:05:38.450 --> 00:05:39.380
be multifaceted.

00:05:39.380 --> 00:05:41.240
We can bring in sponsorships.

00:05:41.240 --> 00:05:43.120
We can monetize our audience directly.

00:05:43.120 --> 00:05:45.800
We can sell merchandise to them directly.

00:05:45.800 --> 00:05:48.720
We can seek philanthropic support.

00:05:49.620 --> 00:05:52.160
We have a consulting piece of our business as well.

00:05:52.160 --> 00:05:55.680
So it really is sort of thinking broadly about how we can

00:05:56.030 --> 00:05:59.440
ignite this audience that we have built that has this kind of

00:05:59.440 --> 00:06:01.980
parasocial relationship with our journalist.

00:06:01.980 --> 00:06:04.880
And they want to support him and his work.

00:06:04.880 --> 00:06:06.980
And we're able to do that in a much more meaningful

00:06:07.020 --> 00:06:08.540
way now that we're independent.

00:06:10.660 --> 00:06:13.170
And Justin, have you seen that as a pattern with other

00:06:13.170 --> 00:06:16.650
creators as well as you speak with people about the Journalism

00:06:16.650 --> 00:06:18.000
Atlas and the way that they're kind of going out in

00:06:18.000 --> 00:06:18.420
the world?

00:06:19.920 --> 00:06:21.580
Yeah, wildly so.

00:06:21.580 --> 00:06:23.720
One of the reasons I'm here.

00:06:23.720 --> 00:06:26.760
You know, this morning I told the anecdote of being at

00:06:26.830 --> 00:06:30.860
The Washington Post in 2011 when the Edward Snowden story breaks

00:06:30.860 --> 00:06:32.560
and all of the interesting parts about the air-gapped

00:06:32.910 --> 00:06:34.920
computer, about Bart Gellman coming to the post,

00:06:34.920 --> 00:06:37.560
of Marty Baron making sense of how we would, you know

00:06:37.560 --> 00:06:39.670
, get the story out there of us having to self-

00:06:39.670 --> 00:06:42.360
aggregate to win audiences back from Google as the aggreg

00:06:42.360 --> 00:06:42.930
ators beat us.

00:06:43.240 --> 00:06:45.080
And then I told the story about Marisa Kavis

00:06:45.080 --> 00:06:47.310
in the last 18 months breaking scoops like crazy on

00:06:47.310 --> 00:06:48.950
Blue Sky and creating this new version of a funnel, right

00:06:49.100 --> 00:06:49.100
?

00:06:49.100 --> 00:06:52.620
Those are two very clean examples of an individual creator-jour

00:06:52.630 --> 00:06:55.010
nalist from a bygone era at this point 15 years

00:06:55.010 --> 00:06:57.560
ago having a brand to protect them and yet still fighting to

00:06:57.560 --> 00:07:00.000
figure out the fidelity information in relation to the audience.

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:01.360
And then Marisa's more recent example.

00:07:01.360 --> 00:07:03.390
As we can't, as I said before, if I

00:07:03.390 --> 00:07:05.580
speak about this, what I find even more is I'm

00:07:05.580 --> 00:07:06.980
listening to this like crazy.

00:07:06.980 --> 00:07:09.360
I mean, Lauren launched six, seven months ago, and

00:07:09.360 --> 00:07:12.100
I still can't stop asking you questions about how you build

00:07:12.100 --> 00:07:12.840
your business.

