00:23:33.920 --> 00:23:34.900
Do we have?

00:23:36.520 --> 00:23:39.870
Thanks.

00:23:39.920 --> 00:23:43.060
Yeah, I had a question.

00:23:43.060 --> 00:23:47.680
You mentioned earlier when you were talking about your start separating from

00:23:47.680 --> 00:23:49.960
the post and the kind of freedoms that that gave you.

00:23:49.960 --> 00:23:52.690
And I hear a lot, like, we're, I

00:23:52.690 --> 00:23:54.820
think there's a lot of developers here and we're building

00:23:54.820 --> 00:23:59.150
infrastructure and the protocol around a lot of the exciting stuff of

00:23:59.150 --> 00:24:02.740
, like, individual content creators and media.

00:24:03.440 --> 00:24:07.500
And then we go back to, like, the support side

00:24:07.700 --> 00:24:11.880
of things and kind of bringing people more together.

00:24:11.880 --> 00:24:15.090
And I was wondering what thoughts you had on, like,

00:24:15.090 --> 00:24:18.120
the transition from, you know, the, like, the

00:24:18.390 --> 00:24:24.430
post and organizations that we have today towards the, kind of

00:24:24.450 --> 00:24:26.580
what your ideal future would look like.

00:24:27.000 --> 00:24:30.780
And how do we build for that on an application or protocol

00:24:30.780 --> 00:24:31.720
or infrastructure level?

00:24:31.720 --> 00:24:33.220
Yeah, thank you for the question.

00:24:33.220 --> 00:24:37.180
I think y'all are primed for that opportunity in

00:24:37.180 --> 00:24:41.290
the way that a lot of traditional organizations are not because we

00:24:41.840 --> 00:24:44.880
weren't able to see the business of the post in many

00:24:44.880 --> 00:24:48.520
aspects sort of reckon with this idea that we had an audience

00:24:48.520 --> 00:24:52.560
that was not interested in the website or the text product.

00:24:52.560 --> 00:24:56.670
And we saw that from a subscription side, from a merchand

00:24:56.670 --> 00:24:59.660
ising side, certainly from an ad and sponsorship side.

00:24:59.660 --> 00:25:03.170
So thinking about the ways that these audiences actually want to support

00:25:03.170 --> 00:25:07.060
the kind of content that independent creators are putting out there is

00:25:07.350 --> 00:25:07.640
essential.

00:25:07.660 --> 00:25:11.180
Like, it's no longer can you sell a subscription to

00:25:11.180 --> 00:25:14.740
the website that will get you around a paywall if you

00:25:14.740 --> 00:25:16.480
are a fan of this TikToker.

00:25:16.480 --> 00:25:19.040
Like, those two things do not reckon with one another anymore

00:25:19.040 --> 00:25:19.200
.

00:25:19.200 --> 00:25:21.780
And I think that's the opportunity of you all is to

00:25:21.780 --> 00:25:27.900
think about what kinds of business support actually honor these audiences where

00:25:27.900 --> 00:25:28.740
they already are.

00:25:28.740 --> 00:25:33.100
And I would just nudge the word parasocial,

00:25:33.100 --> 00:25:35.660
which Lauren said earlier, which is a lot of people's

00:25:35.660 --> 00:25:36.300
relationship with Dave.

00:25:36.300 --> 00:25:38.740
And I heard it in the previous panel talking about music and

00:25:38.740 --> 00:25:39.140
artists.

00:25:39.140 --> 00:25:42.300
But the idea of fandom and parasocial is, I

00:25:42.300 --> 00:25:45.060
think, a wonderful thin layer that connects the concept of any

00:25:45.060 --> 00:25:48.790
type of creation and community that news is moving towards because of

00:25:48.790 --> 00:25:50.540
the destruction of these institutions.

00:25:51.100 --> 00:25:54.040
talented creators like Dave would thrive in that ecosystem, whether it

00:25:54.040 --> 00:25:55.900
's comedy or the next Dave who's not as funny.

00:26:00.320 --> 00:26:01.380
I have a question.

00:26:01.380 --> 00:26:02.740
Hi, Ted.

00:26:02.740 --> 00:26:07.700
So you had talked earlier about how the current state of things

00:26:07.700 --> 00:26:09.000
is not super sustainable.

00:26:09.000 --> 00:26:11.260
Not a big surprise.

00:26:11.260 --> 00:26:14.160
And I just wanted to get from your folks' vantage point

00:26:14.160 --> 00:26:18.000
or from your viewpoint, AI, friend or foe,

00:26:18.000 --> 00:26:21.060
or kind of what are some of the opportunities and scary things

00:26:21.160 --> 00:26:21.760
in this area?

00:26:22.280 --> 00:26:25.680
I'll go for, I mean, inevitability.

00:26:25.680 --> 00:26:27.940
You know, software moves forward.

00:26:27.960 --> 00:26:29.320
Technology moves forward.

00:26:29.320 --> 00:26:31.080
So just to ground it in that.

00:26:31.080 --> 00:26:34.260
I think there are so many conversations to have.

00:26:34.260 --> 00:26:35.480
There's a movement out there.

00:26:35.480 --> 00:26:36.840
I have not been in touch with these folks, but I

00:26:36.840 --> 00:26:37.720
admire their work.

00:26:37.720 --> 00:26:40.640
They identify as RSL, real simple licensing.

00:26:40.640 --> 00:26:44.640
And their construct is just like RSS, having some level

00:26:44.790 --> 00:26:47.720
of mechanism of the, you know, here's the metadata

00:26:47.720 --> 00:26:49.000
that travels with the content.

00:26:49.000 --> 00:26:51.240
I question where that ends up in the long run.

00:26:52.000 --> 00:26:54.010
I think at this moment in time, actually, this is

00:26:54.010 --> 00:26:55.560
the best answer to your question I can give you.

00:26:55.560 --> 00:26:58.050
There is a pretty prominent sub stacker, Lenny Rich

00:26:58.050 --> 00:26:59.500
etsky, if I'm not butchering his last

00:26:59.500 --> 00:26:59.800
name.

00:26:59.800 --> 00:27:00.960
Yeah, Lenny's letter.

00:27:00.960 --> 00:27:04.900
He is a fabulous writer, thinker.

00:27:04.900 --> 00:27:07.520
I forget what his affiliations were professional, which big tech

00:27:07.520 --> 00:27:08.260
companies he worked at.

00:27:08.260 --> 00:27:10.360
But he's been writing for five years or so.

00:27:10.360 --> 00:27:12.820
Just a week or two ago, he published on his sub

00:27:12.990 --> 00:27:17.000
stack his 350 corpus of all previously written stuff and all

00:27:17.000 --> 00:27:20.750
the transcripts of his podcast are being released and licensed to

00:27:21.280 --> 00:27:23.820
anybody with a subscription and a lighter version of it to people

00:27:23.820 --> 00:27:26.420
who are not in markdown form and having a contest to

00:27:26.420 --> 00:27:29.260
see who can create the best stuff off of his IP.

00:27:29.260 --> 00:27:33.000
That, you know, to imagine the Washington Post doing that

00:27:33.000 --> 00:27:35.360
, they think, you know, they are struggling to figure

00:27:35.360 --> 00:27:37.320
out what the open AI will negotiate.

00:27:37.320 --> 00:27:39.580
I've heard in a few of the earlier panels about Reddit

00:27:39.580 --> 00:27:41.330
and the New York Times and their relationship with AI in a

00:27:41.330 --> 00:27:41.740
certain place.

00:27:41.740 --> 00:27:44.560
You know, that's Lenny and he is a product

00:27:44.560 --> 00:27:46.970
person with a certain community doing a certain thing that doesn't

00:27:46.970 --> 00:27:48.140
work for every publisher.

00:27:48.600 --> 00:27:51.720
But the idea of being eyes wide open about the soft horse

00:27:51.720 --> 00:27:53.860
coming with the other, the idea of being eyes wide open

00:27:53.860 --> 00:27:57.820
of what will be the first player multiplayer experience of what could

00:27:58.200 --> 00:28:01.000
happen at a monetization level between machines and even humans,

00:28:01.000 --> 00:28:04.140
I hope that more creator journalists are thinking about that.

00:28:04.140 --> 00:28:05.940
I hope that technologists are thinking about that.

00:28:05.940 --> 00:28:08.300
I think, you know, you guys haven't thought about

00:28:08.300 --> 00:28:09.460
Davebot by chance, have you?

00:28:09.460 --> 00:28:12.400
Or like whatever levels of like, how would you mechanize

00:28:12.400 --> 00:28:15.920
Dave's personality and or use mechanizations to feed more people

00:28:15.920 --> 00:28:17.100
to the real human data?

00:28:17.100 --> 00:28:20.320
We haven't thought about that yet.

00:28:20.320 --> 00:28:25.120
We don't, you know, in our news making,

00:28:25.120 --> 00:28:26.980
we don't really use AI right now.

00:28:26.980 --> 00:28:29.900
Our audience is actually very deeply skeptical of it, at least

00:28:29.900 --> 00:28:31.140
in the video space.

00:28:31.140 --> 00:28:33.840
So we've made a pledge to them that we will not

00:28:33.840 --> 00:28:36.770
use AI in our script writing and in our video production in

00:28:36.770 --> 00:28:37.700
our news gathering.

00:28:37.700 --> 00:28:40.600
And that's part of our kind of like ethics and transparency

00:28:40.600 --> 00:28:41.900
promise to our audience.

00:28:42.220 --> 00:28:43.420
We talk about that a lot.

00:28:43.420 --> 00:28:47.260
We report on AI weekly, sometimes daily.

00:28:47.260 --> 00:28:50.830
But right now, we're not really using it in our

00:28:50.830 --> 00:28:51.600
reporting.

00:28:51.600 --> 00:28:54.400
You know, I think what the future holds is an open

00:28:54.400 --> 00:28:55.060
question.

00:28:55.060 --> 00:28:57.760
But as long as our audience right now is reacting to it

00:28:57.760 --> 00:29:00.960
in the way that they are, especially what they're seeing

00:29:00.960 --> 00:29:03.780
on YouTube, TikTok, Instagram, and sort of like their

00:29:03.780 --> 00:29:07.250
very guttural reaction to it, I think we will

00:29:07.610 --> 00:29:09.340
sort of try to be the antithesis of it.

00:29:09.340 --> 00:29:12.400
I've seen, and you all tell me, comedy is

00:29:12.400 --> 00:29:15.300
one of the things that AI cannot do.

00:29:15.300 --> 00:29:18.200
So as long as Dave can do it and AI doesn't

00:29:18.200 --> 00:29:21.330
do it well, maybe we'll sort of keep it separate

00:29:21.330 --> 00:29:21.580
.

00:29:21.580 --> 00:29:29.750
And if you haven't seen it, Dave

00:29:29.750 --> 00:29:32.430
actually has a character who is the AI character, which we

00:29:32.430 --> 00:29:34.580
kind of regularly kind of, you know.

00:29:34.580 --> 00:29:35.020
Or something.

00:29:35.020 --> 00:29:35.700
Yeah, exactly.

00:29:36.760 --> 00:29:37.020
Hi.

00:29:37.020 --> 00:29:38.910
So in the last five years, I feel like we've

00:29:38.910 --> 00:29:43.450
seen a small resurgence by necessity of like independent media organizations

00:29:43.450 --> 00:29:43.640
.

00:29:43.640 --> 00:29:47.270
I'm thinking of like the 404 defector Flaming

00:29:47.270 --> 00:29:48.420
Hydra aftermath.

00:29:50.200 --> 00:29:54.080
they are notably not on protocol.

00:29:54.080 --> 00:29:56.930
They're, you know, Ghost has been amazing as like

00:29:56.930 --> 00:30:00.200
a democratization platform for them, but it's not connected

00:30:00.200 --> 00:30:00.800
to protocol.

00:30:00.800 --> 00:30:03.030
So I guess my question would be, what would, what

00:30:03.030 --> 00:30:07.550
would be your pitch to them as to, that might ent

00:30:07.550 --> 00:30:10.580
ice them to come over and start publishing on protocol?

00:30:10.580 --> 00:30:13.140
Like what would be the benefit for organizations like that?

00:30:15.720 --> 00:30:17.910
You know, I gave a talk at the beginning of the

00:30:17.910 --> 00:30:19.240
day where I kind of said, hey, I'm here

00:30:19.240 --> 00:30:20.680
as a journalist and here's kind of what I know and

00:30:20.680 --> 00:30:22.230
here's what I'm building a journalism atlas, making

00:30:22.230 --> 00:30:24.000
lists of great journalists and I'm excited to talk to Lauren

00:30:24.000 --> 00:30:25.640
about her business and kind of stand up here.

00:30:25.640 --> 00:30:27.530
We're not on protocol necessarily.

00:30:27.580 --> 00:30:29.820
We're very much coming here with a stance of like,

00:30:29.820 --> 00:30:32.210
we're so curious and interested and that's why the last

00:30:32.210 --> 00:30:34.120
few days have been very inspiring to find some of the folks

00:30:34.120 --> 00:30:37.280
asking, like figuring out what we build with the application layer

00:30:37.280 --> 00:30:39.000
that allow Lauren to, all the things she just talked about

00:30:39.000 --> 00:30:40.950
, doing that on protocol, I think you would do in

00:30:40.950 --> 00:30:43.100
a minute if you thought like, hey, here it is

00:30:43.100 --> 00:30:43.100
.

00:30:43.100 --> 00:30:45.400
But let's find that stuff I think I'd say.

00:30:45.400 --> 00:30:47.120
You want to, anything you would add or?

00:30:47.120 --> 00:30:48.780
No, that's good.

00:30:48.780 --> 00:30:49.380
Yeah.

00:30:49.380 --> 00:30:54.940
I think one of the other things here really is ultimately thinking

00:30:54.940 --> 00:30:58.980
about both what the incentives are for each of these businesses and

00:30:58.980 --> 00:31:03.460
what sorts of affordances do apps give them that either they

00:31:03.460 --> 00:31:06.240
can't get anywhere else or are adequate substitutes for the

00:31:06.240 --> 00:31:07.280
things that they're currently doing.

00:31:07.280 --> 00:31:11.300
And so as we think about these things, like for example

00:31:11.300 --> 00:31:14.730
, exclusivity on any particular platform is probably a non-

00:31:14.730 --> 00:31:15.260
starter.

00:31:15.260 --> 00:31:18.030
And so if you're thinking about that, then the question

00:31:18.030 --> 00:31:20.000
really is how do you grow a particular audience?

00:31:20.000 --> 00:31:24.360
What portion of time do you expect any particular journalist to spend

00:31:24.360 --> 00:31:25.440
with a particular app?

00:31:25.440 --> 00:31:26.780
What do they get out of that?

00:31:26.780 --> 00:31:29.400
So all of those sorts of ROI questions I think are really

00:31:29.400 --> 00:31:33.580
important and thinking about the fact that like essentially all publishing businesses

00:31:33.580 --> 00:31:37.470
are kind of portfolio businesses now and where are they actually der

00:31:37.470 --> 00:31:39.900
iving the revenue and how are they trying to think about their

00:31:39.900 --> 00:31:40.060
time.

00:31:40.780 --> 00:31:41.340
Great answer.

00:31:41.340 --> 00:31:43.300
I think we are at time.

00:31:43.300 --> 00:31:44.440
So thank you so much.

00:31:44.440 --> 00:31:45.920
I really appreciated this conversation.

00:31:45.920 --> 00:31:46.440
It's been great.

00:31:48.010 --> 00:31:49.080
Thank you.
